Date:9/13/2009 10:09:48 AM
From:anializer
Congratulations on 13 years. I find the board to be civil and informative. I've
also have to say that I've picked up some good ideas along the way here, as
well as hopefully shared a few.

As to what has been learned here, like you I'm always learning. After watching
2008 unfold, I'd be inclined to think the direction of the markets are more
important than stock selection. The same for 1999.

When the markets are in decent shape, I'd venture that stock selection is more
important and sound fundamentals matter. But then again, in bull markets they
all go up anyway, so maybe stock selection isn't as big a part in overall
success as I make it to be.

Even though I could have made thousands of percents in the internet bubble, I
failed to see any value whatsoever in the momentum. In retrospect I did not
participate in the internet bubble's rise phase. That was clearly an error
because all that matters is price and making money in this game. And I missed
huge gains sticking to principles.

One the one thing I've learned about myself on the long side i that I have no
patience, particularly in bad markets. My tolerance for deterioration and
erosion of account values is limited and I need to have more conviction and
staying power when I believe in the stock, even through corrections. Not
through massacres though. Still the same problems plague me. How does one
distinguish between an unfolding massacre in a particular stock or markets and
a normal corrective dip?

Is our whole system based on credit and loans, and if so, is that a healthy way
to run an economy. I certainly wouldn't base the running of my household on a
system that requires such massive amounts of debt.

All in all, the disconnect between markets and the underpinnings of our economy
is something that stock traders and investors probably should consider. I've
seen more investors do well and even get rich buying what I'd consider pure
junk. So if the goal is to make money, that needs to be considered as well even
though its not value investing. But I can't adapt to that.

In the end, its what works for a person. For an old dog like me in the market
for 35 years, its difficult to learn new tricks. Like you when portfolios were
high, I bought a Lexus SC430 for cash. I have no idea why except the wife and
kids liked it. After 3 years it still has almost no mileage on it. But a toy
now and again is not bad for one doing well. You can't take it all with you.
Leaving the family in decent shape is probably #1 consideration when I'm gone

I do congratulate you on 13 years here and still thriving. There is only one
other board I celebrated by attending an anniversary party, also a very civil
board with lots of good ideas.

%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:9/13/2009 11:48:21 AM
From:Dale Baker
Since I'm less than six months from my 13th anniversary on SI, I'll chip in
here with a defense of stockpicking. My market timing sucks, but in the long
run, good stockpicking when quality stocks are cheap has produced an annualized
return that a lot of talking heads say can't be done, certainly not by naive
individual investors.

Two things stand out most - first and foremost, I don't buy trouble. I want
cheap stocks but not cheap because they are faltering. I want solid management,
solid profits/cash flow and solid balance sheets (which can be high debt if
it's managed right). Periodically, the market sells off everything and leaves
these gems lying around for us to pick up. Sticking to those rules and being
patient has brought me the best rewards.

Second, I have been 2/3 - 3/4 in international stocks since 2001. We are in the
midst of a long-term global growth story; like the famous bank robber, that's
where you gotta go because that's where the money is. Index investing in the
SP500 has been a failure over the last decade. Playing global growth has not.

I don't post much here because I'm not much of a big cap investor like many
here. But it has been a good read all these years, and I look forward to more.
%EOM----------------------

