Date:9/13/2009 6:22:47 PM
From:Spekulatius
As an investor (or Spekulator? ) I went through different stages. I started out
in the 80's and 90's as a value investor and bought stock based on PE and
historical valuation ranges.

The techstock age
In the late 90's when I moved to the US, I developed more and more an interest
in tech stocks and Biotech stocks - i did decent in the tech bubble but as
anializer said it, I could have done much better. I got out in 99 but kept on
speculating in some Fiber optic stocks (the company I work for was in that
field as well) and did well.
The Biotech age
In 2000, I switched to Biotechs (visiting the Biotech valuation board here on
SI) and initially did well until early 2001 and then I got absolutely hammered.

The Enron and Worldcom age
I sold them all and decided to do something new and went back to my PE metric
based approach. I found utilities that were starting get into problems with the
Enron meltdown. i bought some MIR and EP (amongst other stocks) but realized
soon that something was severely broken and sold these at a loss too. What was
broken of course was that they had way to much debt, funky accounting (non-cash
hedging games etc.). Then there was Worldcom too (I lost a few bucks there as
well) and I beguns studying balance sheet and cash flow statements in more
detail and learned about the treasure trove of SEC filings.

The new bull market age
I probably underperformed during the new bull market. I missed some of the
Y2003 runup (too much cash) but did OK in subsequent years. There were really
not much learnings during the bull market but i did realize that betting on
powerful trends (peak oil) can make a lot of money. never went on that train
though (I exicted early in 2005&2006). The only real eyeopener was "The little
book that beats the market". The main thing I learned from this book was to
look at a company as an acquirer would, which means that one has to take into
account that debt load and adjust the valuation for the Enterprise Value not
the market cap. That is why I tend to compare company more in terms of
EV/EBITDA which is the quickest way to do that without leaving yahoo/finance.

In 2007 I had the feeling that a bank crisis was forthcoming and failed to act
upon it (I do not know how many times I kicked myself during the last 12 month
for that) except selling and staying out most financials. I thought that the
broad economy would not be affect too much by a banking crisis (reapeat the
kicking myself part).

In 2008 I learned about MLPs (great timing -not) and moved 20% of my portfolio
there. In September I realized that something was severely broken in the market
and all bets are off. I stuck with what i considered solid companies and
started to trade much more to take advantage of the volatility (good decision).

During the meltdown i learned more about capital structure arbitage (buying
debt/selling short stocks, "3 letter debt" but most importantly that efficient
market hypothesis is a joke. I never forget that lesson for sure.Going forward
I am thriving to become a better seller (I have been concentrating on getting
good entries but my sell decision process is sloppy) and concentrating more on
international stocks as well.

The board helped me in many ways. First off all the regulars have different
styles and come up with different ideas. Then there is an open critique process
(mostly saying I bought/sold it too). It's sort of funny to think about it but
I'd trust the advice of a bunch of total strangers here on this message board
more than any financial expert or adviser.
%EOM----------------------

