Date:9/13/2009 9:27:55 PM
From:E_K_S
In the 13 years (1996-2009) the portfolio should have grown 4x (double every
7.2 years reflecting a 10% annual return). I still hold six of my top ten
positions from this period and all of them were acquired through periodic buys
(or mergers) since the early 80's. The group pays good dividends and own
interests in large natural resources all over the world.
http://finance.yahoo.com/q?s=CVX,BHP,AAUKY.PK,XOM,AU,AGPPY.PK&d=s

These core holding make up about 30% of my taxable portfolio.

Based on dividends paid and price appreciation 4 of these stocks beat the S&P
500 return (during this 13 year period) and the other two returned even with
the S&P 500. More importantly a large % of the return was due to dividends
earned (about 4% avg) and the rest was from price appreciation (between
6%-10%).
http://finance.yahoo.com/echarts?s=CVX#chart14:symbol=cvx;range=19941201,200909
1;compare=bhp+aauky.pk+xom+au+agppy.pk+
^gspc;indicator=volume;charttype=line;crosshair=on;ohlcvalues=0;logscale=on

Picking the "right" times to buy and the "right" times to sell also impact the
total portfolio return. The biggest position change from this group was my sale
of 1/2 of my platinum holdings in 2007 (ANGLO PLAT UNSP ADR Other OTC:
AGPPY.PK). I was lucky (or exercised the right discipline) by selling this one
near it's all time high. Otherwise, these core holdings have performed quite
well (over the 25 years I have been accumulating) compounding at a rate of 10%
per year (including dividends).

With all of the other events that occurred during this period, some of my
biggest gains were from zero coupon bonds (bought for $0.25/$1.00) which I
purchased in my IRA account in the mid 80's and then sold at $0.96/$1.00 and
moved 60% of this money into preferred REITs in late 2008 and early 2009. These
have since more than doubled in value and (hopefully) has locked in a very good
dividend. The zero coupon bonds increased in value significantly due to the FED
lowing rates to near "0" in 2008. A development I never, ever expected!

I have had my share of losers too! The key is to keep these to a minimum.

I also had some roller coaster "E" rides. One in particular was with Dry Ships
at $9.00/share to $130.00/share and back down to $3.50/share. I learned early
on to take my seed money out (which I did at $60.00/share) but still left a lot
on the table. At $6.76, I still like the company and own shares but my price
expectations have been lowered due to the additional shares sold in 2nd & 3rd
offerings where the company used the proceeds to pay down their huge debt.

Overall I try to buy value and not trade on emotion (fear vs greed). I make a
few less trades each year than I did in the 90's and have focused on building
the portfolio "sectors" rather than loading into one or two individual
speculative/value plays.

This forum has provided good feed back for me on new ideas, finding hidden
value opportunities and helping me confirming my own ideas. The biggest thing I
continue to work at in making my investment decisions is Self-Discipline. That
is create a strategy (based on a theme or under value play), implement it and
give it time to develop. One needs to be patient and disciplined (in both
buying and selling).

My goal is to have the portfolio generate a 10% annual return. By doing
nothing, my core holdings will generally do this over the long term (...be it
13 years or 30 years). Just be prepared to add more stock at the lows and peel
off shares near the highs.

The next 13 years should provide similar excitement but this time it may be due
to a very high interest rate environment.

EKS
