1. Ive learned that there are a lot of people in this world that are a lot
sharper than I and that have much better information than I do.

2. the guy who founded gotham capital who wrote a couple of great books. said
he had 2 rules : you cant trust anyone over 30 and you cant trust anyone under
30. He's right.

3. I have zero ability to judge ceo;s, much better ability to review company
releases to see if they make any sense.

4. I now have zero confidence in the legal system. One simply cant rely on the
law or judges to get your money back after you have been defrauded or cheated.
caveat emptor.

5. if youre sharp enough and dedicated enough you can make a lot of money.
Kudos to Mike Burry wherever you are.

6. If you dont understand the business the company is really in dont invest in
it. In truth its no easy to know what business a company is in and where its
downfall could come from. so we are not really investors we are all
speculators. No one could have predicted the downfall of AIG, except the people
who were taking out mortgage insurance from it, the rest of us were nitwits.

7. Its very dangerous to go against Mr. Market no matter what your logic and
fundamentals are telling you. More often than not there is information out
there we are simply not privy to.
Too often in WEB's vernacular we are the patsy at the poker table.

8. I believe in reading lots of different books and hearing from may different
types of people. Just because I dont like them or what they have to say ,
doesnt mean Im right and they are wrong.

9. Preservation of capital and ability to fight another day is key.

10. Im lucky to have access to such a forum of wise and gifted investors/
speculators who are willing to share their thoughts. thank you all.
