I believe the board has discussed BOARDWALK PIPELINE NYSE: BWP) (which I owned
for six days 7/024/2008 based on Spekulatius heads up buy $22/share to
$24/share) and WILLIAMS COS (NYSE: WMB) that I continue to watch.

I am not too sure if I find any of these companies discussed in the article as
compelling Buys but the article explains why the author likes these specifics
MLP plays.

===============================================================
PWE is another Canadian Energy Trust I own which was upgraded recently. PWE has
a substantial amount of debt from recent property acquisition so they have
reduced their monthly cash distributions to pay down this debt. Therefore, the
NPV of the company increases over time as debt is paid down AND you own a lot
of Oil & NG reserve assets that provides a good hedge against inflation and/or
falling US $.

Penn West Energy Trust's Priorities: Reduce Debt, Exploit Assets - PWE
They see the NPV (standard estimate) of the shares at $19.00 a 33% discount to
the current price of $14.25.

On a current Cash Flow analysis, McDep calculates the per share value at $16.00
a 12.5% discount to the current price.

Here is the link to the detailed Mcdep report.
http://www.mcdep.com/pwe90812.pdf

Conclusion:
Net Present Value - Standard Estimate (US$/sh)19 NPV Approximation by Cash Flow
Multiple Depending on Reserve Life (US$/sh)16

I own both PWE and ERF. Here is a performance graph of both companies.
http://finance.yahoo.com/echarts?s=PWE#chart3:symbol=pwe;range=20070108,2009091
;compare=erf;indicator=volume;charttype=line;crosshair=on;ohlcvalues=0;logscale
on

This is a good way to own proven assets in the ground, obtain a monthly
distribution and protecting your capital to (1) a declining US $ and/or (2)
high inflation.

Management has a pretty good history of developing new reserves and paying off
debt w/ current cash flows. It will be easier as the price of Oil and/or NG
rises. If so, I would expect the monthly distributions would increase too.

